	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Spinoza,<BR>
<BR>
I was at that even with my Cleric on TZ, and I can confirm. I was nuking those Drakes, it worked fine if you stood right next to them. <BR>
<BR>
Anyway, on topic, there was a mage with us there and his pet kicked arse! He was the best tank in the group, it was amazing. Now I'm thinking of trying a mage out. Since I have a full server on TZ I'll have to delete a character or make it on another server - if on TZ of course she will have to be a DE, but if I make one on another server I'll probably go with a gnome. This goes to the guy that asked about what races make good mages. Obviously I haven't played a mage, but I think for the most part I think int casters have the same requirements, and I have played several int casters just not a mage yet. Gnomes and DEs both make very good casters. Dark Elves of course have hide and ultravision as racial advantages. Hide is unfortunately a bit of a waste for pet classes most of the time, since your pet goes kablooey if you hide, and int casters get invis eventually too. Ultravision can be simulated with spells too, although it's damn handy to have it from L1. So I can see how that choice can be written off by some. But still, DEs are without a doubt the best looking race in the game, and make very capable int casters. <BR>
<BR>
Among the lighter races, Erudites get mentioned frequently. And there's nothing wrong with them as casters, to be sure. There are some very nice Erudite only caster items out there. But don't overlook the little Gnomes. They are only a few points below Erudites in int, not enough you're ever likely to notice the difference. Remember stats soft-cap at 200, and if you make an Erudite with max int you're going to hit the soft cap quite easily anyhow. Gnomes also have a lot more dex and agi than erudites, and these stats ARE important to the survival of an int caster. Dex affects spell fizzles, and channelling skill. The tiny advantage in mana that a few points of int will give you hardly make up for that. Agi boosts AC a little, not that it will be greatly noticeable, but when you have few HP anyway, avoiding a blow is even more important. Plus they are small. This IS an advantage. <BR>
<BR>
The remaining races you can make a mage with are High Elves and Humans. Humans have very balanced stats, but they're blind as a bat at night until you get many levels and acquire spells to enhance your sight. High elves should make fine casters. <BR>
<BR>
In the end, remember that stats don't mean a whole lot in this game - it's been coded to avoid making these the end all and be all, and frankly it's stats have been coded almost out of consideration. You need a very large difference (say 20+ points) to have any chance of noticing it. It's certainly not worth playing a character you think is ugly or who lacks an ability you want for a handful of points one way or another, even in a prime attribute. 
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
